                            <comment id="19655" author="robh" created="Thu, 14 Sep 2006 21:26:55 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;AnnotationTransactionAspect now advises:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;1. Any public method in an @Transactional type&lt;br/&gt;
2. Any non-private @Transactional method.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We decided that @Tansactional types should only have public methods advised by default, and that private methods should never be advised.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Rob&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="19656" author="springboy" created="Thu, 14 Sep 2006 21:30:28 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Will document this in the Spring reference documentation forthwith.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="19657" author="ralfebert" created="Thu, 14 Sep 2006 22:00:29 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&amp;gt; We decided that @Tansactional types should only have public methods advised by default, and that private methods should never be advised.&lt;br/&gt;
What&apos;s the reason for not advising private methods? For example, let&apos;s say you have a DAO class with a typical DAO method and want a part of this method to be executed in its own transaction. I can use programatic transaction demarcation of course, but if working with AspectJ annotations, I would also consider refactoring the part into a separate method (if it needs a separate transaction, its probably a good candidate for a separate method anyway) and use an @Transactional annotation to declare the transaction behaviour (and not clutter up the code, for such things I would prefer a simple annotation over the TransactionalTemplate). Any good reason not to do such things / not to support this?&lt;br/&gt;
Of course, this is only an option if you use plain AspectJ aspects without Spring proxies. I never liked the &quot;aspects using proxies&quot; approach, because if I call a method on &quot;this&quot; which is advised, I expect the advice to be active. If I declare a method as Transactional, I want this transactional behaviour on every call to this method &lt;em&gt;without_any_exception&lt;/em&gt;. I thought with the AspectJ support in Spring 2.0 this is explicitly supported, so why not provide suitable aspects for such configurations?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="19661" author="robh" created="Thu, 14 Sep 2006 23:14:01 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;For docs&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
